CREATE FUNCTION _pgr_cuthillMckeeOrdering(
```
PostgreSQL automatically converts everything to lower case.
`_pgr_cuthillMckeeOrdering` -> `_pgr_cuthillmckeeordering`

Then postgres will look on the C files the function that has name:  `_pgr_cuthillmckeeordering`

std::cout << "original bandwidth: " << bandwidth(G) << std::endl;
kinda they gave additional information about the original data.

To get the bandwidth, `pgr_bandwidth` would be a nice function to write. (not inthe scope of your proposal)

So based on that example and that hypothetically `boost_example` has the graph data: 
```
pgr_bandwidth($SELECT * FROM boost_example$),  -> 8
pgr_bandwidth(pgr_cuthillMckeeOrdering($SELECT * FROM boost_example$)) -> 4
```
The first result is the original_bandwith
the second result is the new_bandwidth

For this function this is (aprox) needed as result: (a column seq, that keeps an ordering, not shown here)

8 
3 
0 
9 
2 
5 
1 
4 
7 
6
```

If you dont want this to be processed use the configuration.conf at the root of the repository for controlling.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 6, 30, 0, 56, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cvvergara', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 910518290, 'comment_body': 'remove this useless comment.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 6, 30, 0, 56, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cvvergara', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 910519695, 'comment_body': 'Do not use camelCase on the function name on the C code:

If SQL says: (Use camel case here is ok)
```
CREATE FUNCTION _pgr_cuthillMckeeOrdering(
```
PostgreSQL automatically converts everything to lower case.
`_pgr_cuthillMckeeOrdering` -> `_pgr_cuthillmckeeordering`

Then postgres will look on the C files the function that has name:  `_pgr_cuthillmckeeordering`
If a different name is used on the C file, postgres will never find it.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 6, 30, 1, 1, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cvvergara', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 910524321, 'comment_body': 'This does not look right.
maybe you took the term of bandwith from this example:
https://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_78_0/libs/graph/example/cuthill_mckee_ordering.cpp
But that is calculated with:
std::cout << "original bandwidth: " << bandwidth(G) << std::endl;
kinda they gave additional information about the original data.

```
pgr_bandwidth($SELECT * FROM boost_example$),  -> 8
pgr_bandwidth(pgr_cuthillMckeeOrdering($SELECT * FROM boost_example$)) -> 4
```
The first result is the original_bandwith
the second result is the new_bandwidth

```
